                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1066">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/2887½: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-13T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 13, 1929—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>152. Your 208, Reparation No. 240. We based our computations on 4 percent of
                    average annuity of 1988 million. Service of the loan was not taken into
                    consideration in making these calculations, but as the 79 million gold marks
                    takes care both of mixed claims and our Army costs in 37 years at an interest
                    rate of 3½ percent for deferred payments on latter, we are willing to stand on
                    figures sent you in Department’s telegram No. 148. The sentence to which you
                    refer was inserted for purpose of making sure that the 1988 million included all
                    reparations, thus including reparations in kind, to all creditors.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
